  "prompt_text": "What is the time complexity of merge sort and why? Walk through the recurrence relation.",
  "response_text": "The time complexity of merge sort is \\(O(n \\log n)\\), where \\(n\\) is the number of elements in the array being sorted. This complexity arises from the divide-and-conquer approach that merge sort uses.\n\n### Recurrence Relation for Merge Sort\n\nMerge sort works by recursively dividing the array into two halves until each subarray contains a single element. Then, it merges those subarrays back together in a sorted manner. The recurrence relation for the time complexity \\(T(n)\\) can be expressed as:\n\n\\[ T(n) = 2T\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right) + O(n) \\]\n\nHere's a breakdown of the components of this recurrence relation:\n\n1. **Divide Step**: The array is divided into two halves, which takes \\(O(1)\\) time. However, since we do this recursively on both halves, the cost of the division step is not significant in terms of the overall complexity.\n\n2. **Conquer Step**: Each half is sorted independently. If the size of each half is \\(n/2\\), then the time to sort each half is \\(T\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\). Since there are two halves, the total time for sorting both halves is \\(2T\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\).\n\n3. **Combine Step**: Merging the two sorted halves takes \\(O(n)\\) time because every element must be compared and placed in the correct position in the merged array.\n\nCombining these steps, we get the recurrence relation:\n\n\\[ T(n) = 2T\\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right) + O(n) \\]\n\nTo solve this recurrence relation, we can use the Master Theorem, which applies to recurrences of the form \\(T(n) = aT\\left(\\frac{n}{b}\\right) + f(n)\\), where \\(a \\geq 1\\), \\(b > 1\\), and \\(f(n)\\) is an asymptotically positive function.\n\nIn our case:\n- \\(a = 2\\)\n- \\(b = 2\\)\n- \\(f(n) = O(n)\\)\n\nAccording to the Master Theorem, when \\(f(n) = O(n^c)\\) and \\(c < \\log_b a\\), the solution to the recurrence is \\(T(n) = O(n^{\\log_b a})\\). Here, \\(c = 1\\) and \\(\\log_b a = \\log_2 2 = 1\\), so \\(c = \\log_b a\\). When \\(f(n) = \\Theta(n^{\\log_b a})\\), the solution is \\(T(n) = \\Theta(n^{\\log_b a} \\log n)\\).\n\nThus, the time complexity of merge sort is \\(O(n \\log n)\\).\n\n---\n\nVCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\n",
